nsive experience working with Annual Giving staff, and was responsible for growing the President?s Society group and assisted in Major Gift work in conjunction with the first comprehensive campaign for ISU.  She spent a little over a year working in Sales and Marketing at Westminster Village in Terre Haute where she developed a deep appreciation for those who provide care for seniors. She has also worked in staffing development and corporate sales roles.\r\n\r\nDanyelle is proud to, once again, join the non-profit world and be a part of an organization that is caring for its members and families.\r\n\r\nIn her spare time, she has participates volunteer activities, including Ronald McDonald house and the YMCA, and particpates in different league sports.\r\n\r\n<strong><big>Steve Sonafrank</big></strong>\r\n<img src="http://www.scxserv.com/imhf/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/steve-202x300.jpg" alt="" title="steve" width="202" height="300" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-143" />A native of Bunker Hill, Indiana, Steve attended Maconaquah High School and graduated from Indiana University in 1988, where he played trombone in the Marching Hundred and earned a bachelor of science degree in education.  He later taught English at Maconaquah High School and served as speech coach. He most recently served as a sales associate at W.H. Paige & Company in Indianapolis.\r\n\r\nHe has served as an elder at Irvington Presbyterian Church, board member at Epworth Forest Choir School, and president of the board for the Indiana University Marching Hundred Alumni Band.\r\n\r\nBrother Sonafrank was raised a Master Mason in 2002 at Bunker Hill Lodge No.683, where he is a Past Master.  He served concurrently as Worshipful Master, Grand Steward & Tyler, and Indiana Masonic Home board member in 2006-07.  In the Scottish Rite, he is currently Master of Ceremonies in the officer line of the Indianapolis Chapter of Rose Croix.\r\n\r\nIn his spare time, he enjoys playing trombone in the Scottish Rite Orchestra as well as in the Christ Presbyterian Church brass ensemble. He follows both Indiana University athletics and the Indianapolis Colts. When IU won the national basketball championship in 1987, he witnessed the victory from the front row of the IU basketball band in the New Orleans Superdome.  He also enjoys swimming, biking, yard work, and tinkering with his antique Maytag wringer washing machine.\r\n\r\nSteve and his wife Jenny first met while college students in the IU Marching Hundred.  They were married at Irvington Presbyterian Church in 1996 and live in Indianapolis.\r\n\r\n<strong><big>Jeffery P. Zaring</big></strong>\r\n<img src="http://www.scxserv.com/imhf/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/jeffzaring-300x200.jpg" alt="" title="jeffzaring" width="300" height="200" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-146" />Jeffery P. Zaring has served as Executive Director of the Indiana Masonic Home Foundation since May 1, 2011. A native of Indianapolis, Jeff attended the Indianapolis Public Schools. His undergraduate and graduate studies were at Indiana University, Bloomington, and the Indiana University School of Law at Indianapolis. While a law student, he was employed by the Indiana University Police Department and graduated from the Indiana Law Enforcement Academy. He began a 33-year career with the Indiana Department of Education in 1977, working first as a consultant to police school liaison programs. At his retirement in April 2011, he served as Chief of Results and Reform and State Board of Education Administrator. His responsibilities included implementing federal and state school accountability laws, including the federal No Child Left Behind Act, and guiding policy development for the Indiana State Board of Education as its executive director. \r\n\r\nJeff was raised in Brownsburg Lodge No. 241 F&AM in 1978 and served as Worshipful Master in 1983. He also is a member of Calvin W. Prather Lodge No. 717 in Indianapolis. In 2008-2009, he served as the 158th Grand Master of Masons in Indiana.\r\n\r\nHe was created a Sovereign Grand Inspector General, 33°, in September 2004, and served as the Potentate of Murat Temple in 2005. Other Masonic memberships include the Prather York Rite bodies, Sahara Grotto, Tall Cedars of Lebanon, Red Cross of Constantine, York Rite College, Yeomen of York, Allied Masonic Degrees, National Sojourners, Heroes of 76, and the Royal Order of Scotland. He is the High Priest of the Hendricks County York Rite chapter, U.D. Jeff is a Past Patron of Brownsburg Chapter No. 266, Order of the Eastern Star.\r\n\r\nJeff and Margie, his wife of 37 years, live in Fishers. Margie is a member of the Executive Committee of the Indianapolis Symphony Orchestra Association and a member of the PEO Sisterhood. Jeff and Margie attend First United Methodist Church in Noblesville. His primary hobby is playing the bagpipes with the Murat Highlanders. ', 'Staff', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '28-revision-14', '', '', '2012-07-27 03:42:17', '2012-07-27 03:42:17', '', 28, 'http://www.scxserv.com/imhf/28-revision-14/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
